attributes.title: Peleliu: WWII's Most Well-Preserved Battlefield
attributes.description_short: The remote island of Peleliu is the most well-preserved WWII battlefield anywhere.
attributes.description_long: The remote island of Peleliu is considered the most well-preserved battlefield in the world. It is illegal to remove any relic from the island, so the battlefield remains almost as it was when the fight here ended in the fall of 1944. This year marks the 80th anniversary of the Marine and Army battle, which was supposed to last three days, but instead took 72 days of hard fighting.

attributes.title: My King Charles
attributes.description_short: Stories and insights from those close to the King at the most pivotal moments of his life.
attributes.description_long: Stories and insights from the people close to the King at the most pivotal moments of his life, painting a uniquely intimate picture of the real man behind the crown.

attributes.title: Free Exercise: America's Story of Religious Liberty
attributes.title_sortable: Free Exercise: America's Story of Religious Liberty
attributes.description_short: Explore religious freedom in the U.S. through six faith communities and recent challenges.
attributes.description_long: America’s Founding Fathers enshrined the free exercise of religion in the First Amendment, viewing it as vital to a perfect Union. A new documentary hosted by Richard Brookhiser explores this history, spanning 500 years and two continents, highlighting key events—from George Washington’s support for Jewish inclusion to the Underground Railroad—while asking what this commitment means today.

attributes.title: VOCES American Historia: The Untold History of Latinos
attributes.title_sortable: VOCES American Historia: The Untold History of Latinos
attributes.description_short: Join John Leguizamo on a journey into the rich and often overlooked history of Latinos.
attributes.description_long: Join creator and host John Leguizamo on a quest to uncover Latino and Latina heroes and their contributions. Leguizamo takes viewers on a captivating journey, delving into both well-known and lesser-known stories of Latino history, spanning thousands of years, from the Ancient Empires to the present, and shining a light on the rich and often overlooked history of Latinos.
attributes.funder_message: Funding for American Historia is provided, in part, by PBS, the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, the Anderson Family Charitable Fund, Sue and Edgar Wachenheim III, The WNET Group’s Chasing the Dream initiative, the Ford Foundation/JustFilms, and Seton J. Melvin.

attributes.title: Iconic America
attributes.description_short: In this new docuseries, David Rubenstein explores the meaning of America’s iconic symbols.
attributes.description_long: In this new eight-episode documentary series, David Rubenstein explores America’s 400-year history through a close examination of iconic national symbols such as the Hollywood Sign, Fenway Park, American cowboys and the Statue of Liberty: indelible artifacts, places, and archetypes. Each episode tells the story of an American symbol to reveal its origins, significance and the arc of its resonance.
attributes.funder_message: Iconic America: Our Symbols and Stories with David Rubenstein is a production of Show of Force, DMR Productions, and WETA Washington, D.C. David M. Rubenstein is the host and executive producer. Maro Chermayeff, Jeff Dupre, Joshua Bennett and Sam Pollard are executive producers for Show of Force. John F. Wilson is executive producer for WETA. Bill Gardner is the executive in charge for PBS. Chris Ullman is producer for DMR Productions. Jonathan Scheinberg, Prisca Pointdujour, Sam Lacroix, Alexandra Nikolchev, Sally Rosenthal, Matthew Horovitz, Lizzie Mulvey and Ken Levis are producers for Show of Force. Kate Kelly is producer for WETA. Rick Van Meter is supervising producer. Allison Hanna is archival producer. Gary Lionelli is composer for the original score. Funding is provided by The Zohar and Lisa Ben-Dov Family through the Luminescence Foundation.

attributes.title: Baseball
attributes.description_short: An American epic overflowing with heroes and hopefuls, scoundrels and screwballs.
attributes.description_long: The story of Baseball is the story of America. It is an epic overflowing with heroes and hopefuls, scoundrels and screwballs. It is a saga spanning the quest for racial justice, the clash of labor and management, the transformation of popular culture, and the unfolding of the national pastime.
attributes.funder_message: Funding Provided By: General Motors Corporation; The National Endowment for the Humanities; The Pew Charitable Trusts; The Corporation for Public Broadcasting; The Public Broadcasting Service; Arthur Vining Davis Foundations

attributes.title: Osborne House: A Royal Retreat
attributes.description_short: An up-close and personal glimpse into Osborne House, Queen Victoria's favorite home.
attributes.description_long: An up-close and personal glimpse into Osborne House, Queen Victoria's favorite home, where she and her husband came to escape the pressures of royal life.

attributes.title: Major Taylor: Champion of the Race
attributes.title_sortable: Major Taylor: Champion of the Race
attributes.description_short: The first Black sports superstar. Reporters called him “The Fastest Man in the world"
attributes.description_long: Major Taylor: Champion of the Race retraces the life and legacy of an American civil rights pioneer who set more than 20 world records in speed cycling during the heart of Jim Crow America. Major Taylor captured the world cycling championship, the American cycling crown, and had set dozens of world speed cycling records – all while having to endure withering racial pressures.

attributes.full_common_name: WTVP, Public Media for Central Illinois

attributes.title: Pompeii: The New Dig
attributes.description_short: A landmark series following the biggest archaeological dig at Pompeii for a generation.
attributes.description_long: The series follows the biggest archaeological excavation in Pompeii for a generation. Exciting discoveries and fresco-inspired animations tell the story of life in Pompeii AD 79. It also imagines the horrors faced by resident as Vesuvius erupted.

attributes.title: American Muslims: A History Revealed
attributes.description_short: Six short films revealing and exploring the untold histories of Muslims in America.
attributes.description_long: American Muslims: A History Revealed is a series of six short documentary films that reveal and explore the early history of Muslims in America. The series is hosted by three leading American Muslim journalists: Malika Bilal, Aymann Ismail, and Asma Khalid. Over the course of the series, they travel the country to piece together stories spanning over 200 years.

attributes.title: Roots of Resistance
attributes.description_short: Have you ever looked around and wondered how society transformed into what it is today?
attributes.description_long: Have you ever looked around and wondered how society transformed into what it is today? Felecia For the Win is here to shed some light on it all. On Roots of Resistance we'll take a deep dive into various social movements, and into the individuals who helped create them, that have shaped how we exist today.

attributes.title: Wisconsin Hometown Stories
attributes.description_short: Stories about the people, businesses, and events that shaped Wisconsin.
attributes.description_long: Telling Wisconsin's history one town at a time, this series of documentaries highlights the people, businesses and events that shaped communities throughout Wisconsin.

attributes.title: And Knowledge to Keep Us
attributes.description_short: An Alaskan camp leads a race against time to repatriate and reawaken Sugpiaq culture.
attributes.description_long: Every year Sugpiat kids gather for Akhiok Kids Camp to connect with and celebrate knowledge their Ancestors grew for over 7500 years. But a barrier lies between the kids and their Ancestors: 200 years of colonial suppression that reduced their words to whispers. The Camp is part of the race against time to repatriate and reawaken Sugpiaq knowledge and culture.

attributes.full_common_name: WTVP, Public Media for Central Illinois

attributes.title: Coming To Mni Sota
attributes.description_short: Coming To Mni Sota spans hundreds of years, telling the story of multitudes of people.
attributes.description_long: Coming to Mni Sota explores conflicts, contradictions and solidarity among the millions who have moved to and through Minnesota. For centuries, arrivals from around the world have changed Minnesota's identity and the lives of those already here. By examining these intertwining narratives, unique stories reveal a greater shared understanding. Made possible by the Arts and Cultural Heritage Fund.

attributes.title: Crash Course Religions
attributes.description_short: Let's explore the history and culture of religions and how they help us to make sense of our lives.
attributes.description_long: Welcome to Crash Course Religions! Over the next 24 episodes, John Green will explore the history and culture of religions and how they offer frameworks for making sense of our lives — while being incredibly slippery things to pin down. We’ll discover how we define, debate, and contest what religion means, whether we’re personally religious or not. Episode 1 premieres on September 10, 2024.

attributes.title: The Bomb
attributes.description_short: Learn the powerful story of the most destructive invention in human history.
attributes.description_long: A powerful story of the most destructive invention in human history, outlining how America developed the nuclear bomb, how it changed the world and how it continues to loom large in our lives. Witness the raw power and strangely compelling beauty of rare views of above-ground nuclear tests.

attributes.title: The National Parks
attributes.description_short: The story of an idea as American as the Declaration of Independence and just as radical.
attributes.description_long: Filmed over the course of more than six years at some of nature's most spectacular locales, the film is a story of people from every conceivable background—rich and poor, soldiers and scientists, natives and newcomers—who were willing to devote themselves to saving some precious portion of the land they loved and in doing so reminded their fellow citizens of the full meaning of democracy.
attributes.funder_message: Major funding is provided by General Motors, Evelyn & Walter Haas,Jr. Fund, CPB; Bank of America; The Arthur Vining Davis Foundations; Park Foundation, Inc; PBS; National Park Foundation; The Peter Jay Sharp Foundation and the Pew Charitable Trusts.

attributes.title: Gods of Tennis
attributes.description_short: Revisit how the tennis golden age changed the game forever in this three-part fascinating series.
attributes.description_long: Framed through the world-famous Wimbledon tournament, revisit the golden age of tennis in this three-part fascinating series. Meet the heroes who changed the sport forever and drove significant change away from the tennis courts.

attributes.title: North Korea: A Filmmaker Walks the Tightrope
attributes.title_sortable: North Korea: A Filmmaker Walks the Tightrope
attributes.description_short: A striking a tenuous balance of love, politics and history.
attributes.description_long: The parents of filmmaker Yang Yonghi, activists in a pro-North association of Japanese Korean residents, sent Yonghi's three brothers to live in North Korea when they were still in their teens. During the decades of separation that followed, Yonghi used her films to explore conflicted feelings about her family. Her search for identity continues and is captured through this documentary.

attributes.full_common_name: WTVP, Public Media for Central Illinois

attributes.title: Forgotten Fame: The Marion Miley Story
attributes.title_sortable: Forgotten Fame: The Marion Miley Story
attributes.description_short: The story of the headline-grabbing crime that cut short the life of a pioneering athlete.
attributes.description_long: Professional athletics were deemed improper for women in the 1930s, and trailblazing golfer Marion Miley’s exceptional talent and winning personality captivated sports fans across the country. At age 27, Marion was tragically murdered in her home at the Lexington Country Club in Kentucky. This film tells the story of the headline-grabbing crime that cut short the life of this pioneering athlete.
